content: It certainly makes it easy to transfer files to or from another system via wifi--I've never had much luck transferring files via USB to my desktop Linux system. The bad part? It is *dog* *slow*. I have 5 GHz wifi and gigabit internet where I live. Speedtest on my phone shows me pulling down and uploading around 200 Mb/s. OTOH, as I type, in another tab on this browser I see my phone downloading files using WiFi File Transfer Pro. It nicely shows an indication of how fast the data is moving. How fast? All of 0.02 MB/s. That would be something like 0..2 Mb/s, a whole 1/1000th the speed that Speedtest shows my phone is capable of. It's been going a couple of hours, and made it a whole 5% of the way through the transfer of 7GB, rather than being over and done with in a few minutes. I do note that when uploading, the app creates a .zip file and sends that rather than pulling down one file at a time as it's doing now, which may very well be a major source of overhead. Which reminds me--there's no button to push on the web page via which one transfer files to let me break out of this mind-numbingly slow file transfer.

Writing a review because allot of reviews are outright wrong. This app supports 2 methods of uploads, flash and direct using HTML 5. Yes Chrome does not support flash anymore, but the other method works fine. Additionally: "but it's slower than a wired connection with usb-C" This is simply incorrect, with WiFi 5 or WiFi 6 (AC or AX respectively) get 100+MBps, the speed you get out depends on your WiFi connection, a few reviews say they get slow speed, this app is not the bottle neck. this app can access SD cards with no problems as well. This is a fantastic app that is quick to set up and is universal, but due to not understand the issue, negative reviews have been posted. Another app won't fix a slow WiFi connection. It even has support for holding shift to select multiple files, this sounds like a simple feature but it's a quality of life enhancement that elevates it from a simple "file transfer tool" to a true file manager.
For what it is, it's decent. But it hasn't been updated since 2013. Wouldn't mind if it was updated now and then, not just completely abandoned

For me this app seems to transfer data around 10MB/s, which I think is actually pretty good for WiFi, but it is still not as good as the straight USB 3 connection I have. For transferring videos, this speed is incredibly important, and so I will likely not be using this app as a regular method of transferring files. On top of that, the GUI seems old and outdated. It also doesn't do a very good job of mimicking the directory structure of the phone and memory card. The emulated filestructure is very confusing and seems to be missing folders. I was able to pull files from the memory (SD) card, but there was nothing intuitive about how to find the files. I'm still not even certain that I would be able to find all the different files and folders as they exist on the memory card. I think perhaps this app may only recognize and display known media files (don't quote me on that though). Transferring multiple files at once is also clunky as you have to save the files individually, and with Chrome, it seems you can only download 5 at a time, and so you have to wait until the first one of those five completes before more "Save As.." dialog boxes pop up for the 6th file, then wait some, then "Save As..." another, etc... This is very interruptive! I'm going to keep this app on my device as a backup, but I will not be buying it again.

I've been using this app for over a year. It transfers pictures and videos and probably any other file large or small. It does what you would expect it to do and does it well. I put a little icon on my desktop (pic phone swap). Open the program on you phone, then hit the icon on the desktop (I used the link provided when the phone app started), If you're doing pictures make sure that you navigate to the right place before starting to download. It's like file explorer. Like file explorer if you move the wrong things around, you can lose stuff. It gives you the option of compressing all the selection of files into one zip file for later extraction. Give the zip file a different name each time. Try extracting them before deleting anything. It can take time for the phone to make the compressed file. It also take WiFi time to transfer it. Look at the bottom of your computer screen to see the progress. Have you never used compressed files? Making the zip file is optional. Read up then. It doesn't get simpler than this program. You can also bypass compression and download files separately or in a bunch without compression.

A very good app.  If you are always connecting cables to your devices, then this is a good application.  the app tricks your android device to think it's a network router.  But it does not service as a router.  But that is not impossible.  Just like configuring a Linksys or NetGear network router, you enter a IP address given by the app into your web browser on your pc.  I do have some warnings.  Hackers love to attack network routers.  Using the same networking interface gives hackers an unwanted portal into your device if discovered.  I would recommend caution using the app for this reason.    Linksys, for example, uses a app to allow admins to remotely configure your network.  They can also see into your network as per end user agreement.  Issues to think about while using the app.

Update to my review: If you are trying to access your external SD card, there is no longer a link for it on the home page GUI.  You now have to hit the home page GUI, then browse the root directory for it.  Pay attention to what is written after the "Current Directory:"  If you want to read/write to or from your external SD card, just browse to:  /storage/extSdCard/  It's  that simple.  When you do this, it will say: Current Directory: /storage/extSdCard/  All of the contents of the external SD card will be available here, but it will not show the size of the SD card on the right side of the screen...still shows my 11.47Gb internal storage capacity but at least I know how big my external SD card is and my phone can tell me the available space on it.   Original Review:  Forget the cables for PC to mobile or even mobile to mobile transfer.  Have you ever purchased a non-OEM cable for your phone and tried to transfer data from your PC to your phone just to find out that your PC can't recognize your device with that cable.  You can now keep those cheap after market cables for charging and just use this app for your data transfers.  Great price and very convenient for file sharing.

With an 802.11n or 802.11ac connection at 5GHz, this is truly a beautiful app.  Set your home network, and as soon as you connect to your home network you can access (nearly) all of the files on your local phone's storage and any connected external drives (microSD card, etc.).  While perhaps not as fast as a direct cable connection, the ease-of-use and convenience far outweigh any concern there.  Three years later, I find it to still be well worth the one-time expense.  If you set your router to use the same IP address (by DHCP reservation) for your phone/tablet/Android device, creating a bookmark/favorite is effortless and will allow you to access your files at any time.  This is particularly useful in my case when taking multiple photographs for use on eBay listings -- sort by time, download, and list!  I am very happy with my purchase.

I have been using the Pro version of this app, over several years and with many phones. And each time it works to perfection. In an area that most fail. We need to exchange data between our phones and PC (I have used it with Windows, Linux as well as Mac) and this app makes it an enjoyable process. Especially for Versions running Kitkat and above, where usb connections are an issue for most, this app is a complete blessing.  I have tried others in passing. Airdroid is good, but is more for using your computer screen instead of your phone screen, for WA, SMS calls etc. However, where exclusive file management is concerned, in my humble opinion this app beats them all, hands down.  It is fast, intuitive, reliable with an easy to work with UI. I use it to very quickly organise files on my phone as well, even if transfers are not required. I highly recommend reading the instructions, which takes just a few minutes.   In short, GET IT! You won't regret it.

In my first 2 minutes I found some important flaws, among them the following:  * NOT AJAX-enabled -- not using AJAX is an annoying habit from back in the 90s when AJAX was hard. * Flash uploader doesn't work for folders on Chromium and Galaxy SIII * When you create a folder, it pops up a system dialog, and the title isn't automatically selected, so you have to actually go and click and select it to set it.  That's just a few specific little details, but overall, the interface could use some help. These things were all problems in the Free version, but of course it was free so I didn't complain. Now that I've paid, I'd like these extremely simple issues addressed.  Thanks, Kael

It's brainless easy to use, also.  For reference, a full length movie now takes ~90 seconds instead of 10 minutes.  An entire 32gb phone backup now takes 75 minutes instead of 9 hours. This is a very nice app for wireless file transers, but it has some serious bugs that need to be worked out for Mac OS users. If you set a password to protect your device, transfers stop working -- when you try to kick off an upload or download in your web browser, it prompts you for the password in a flashing text box that doesn't permit you to type anything. Disabling password protection in the app's settings allow the transfer to proceed.   The obvious workaround for this is to hit the "Stop" button after you do your transfer, shutting down the app. Most likely, none of your neighbors will happen to be searching for mobile devices to hack into in the couple minutes that you're using the app -- but you are leaving your device wide open, so be careful.   ALSO: The app will only send files to the root directory of your device's internal storage. If you want to put the file on your SD card, or a different folder in internal storage, you have to do that as a separate step. If you do this 2nd step through this app's "Move" button, it requires you to type the file path by hand (e.g. "/storage/emulated/0/Movies"). It would be much nicer to be able to navigate by clicking on folders!

Unfortunately this is due to a change in Android 4.4. Google no longer allows apps to write to the external card as a matter of policy. Very unfortunate decision in my opnion, but they're trying to simplify the file system for novice users, and sadly there's no way to get around it because the operating system has the final say about file access.

After I updated my Note 3 to 4.4.2 it stopped working. After experimenting I have found that I can only transfer to my phones internal memory, but not to the SD card. Update... Received a response from the developer about this issue, he said, Unfortunately Google has changed the access permissions in Android 4.4, so third party apps are no longer able to write to the SD card at all. This applies to all apps, and there doesn't seem to be a way to get around this restriction without rooting the device. The operating system has the final say over file access permissions. Essentially Google is trying to simplify the file system for novice users, so they're restricting apps to the internal storage to make it easier for users to find their files. As you can imagine, many people including myself are quite unhappy with this change.I really wish I could do more to help, but I'm afraid my hands are tied in this case.

If you consider this as alternative to usb cable file transfer, then I must say that the file transfer speed over WiFi is very slow. Took me around 20 minutes to transfer 800mb file. Is this normal?
replyContent:
The speed depends on the quality of the wifi connection. Your device (Nexus 7 2012) supports 802.11n at 65 Mbit/s max, which should yield about 4.5 megabytes per sec in practice, assuming a good signal.
If you're only getting around 1.3 MB/sec, the 2.4 GHz spectrum in your area may be crowded, so you may want to find a less congested channel.

content: It's a great app. Really easy to transfer files!!!

Works great! I use it to transfer lots of files to and from my rooted Nook Tablet running 4.2.2. The transfer speed is excellent, and the web interface is clean, quick, and easy to understand.   Look no further - this is the file transfer app you want! :)  I've encountered some issues, but none of them are caused by the app itself - if Wifi File Transfer PRO crashes, or your device reboots suddenly, check to see if another app is running in the background causing issues - in my case "The Simpsons: Tapped Out" was causing the problem, and the fault was not with Wifi File Transfer Pro.  Two recommendations/wish lists for future versions of the app:  1. Option to 'keep wifi alive' while in use. On my device, when the screen goes to sleep, Wifi drops, terminating any transfers in progress.   2. An on-screen indication on the Android device as to what is being done would be nice - I often step away from the PC and would like to see how the file transfers are going on the Android devices' screen instead of the static start/stop button.
Definitely worth the money, must buy on Play store.

Well, that's my opinion and as a long time user of Wifi File Transfer Pro I feel entitled to state it pretty much emphatically. I'll be honest and say that I do tend to use a lot of the free versions of many apps that are available, but from the very first time I used this one I knew it was worth the asking price so basically within an hour of using it once I purchased it and haven't regretted it for a single second. Using Wifi File Transfer Pro on my home network (and others as required) saves me a lot of wear and tear on my Samsung Galaxy S4 Active microUSB port - I even have the wireless charger for it too so I rarely have to open the little water-resistant protective cover on it.  So if you're sick of swapping cables and plugging/unplugging over and over again just to move some files around, or sick of popping the back cover off to get the microSD card out if you have a phone with one, this is the app for you. Sure it's a bit slower than a true USB wired connection, but considering how much some repair shops charge to fix those microUSB ports when they break, this app pays for itself the first time you'll use it, seriously.  Don't thank me, thank the developer when you do.

When Google decided to "upgrade" their OS on my Galaxy Nexus, I could no longer tether my phone to the PC and download my photos from the phone to the hard drive. I use my phone camera a LOT, and got warnings on my phone that I was just about out of room and had to clear some space on it. To keep the phone from crashing and losing the files on my phone, I started to use Google Drive to upload the files to the cloud and then download them from there. What a slow and painstaking process that turned out to be!  Then I found this gem of an app. I paid the $1.49 for the Pro version since many of my video files are well over the 5MB limit on the free version. WOW! I am very impressed with not only how much faster and easier it is over doing it through Google Drive, but it even blows away the performance of the software on the phone that is supposed to be used to do the transfers. Because my phone was so full of pics & videos (24G), it took a few minutes to load everything, but once it did, it was very easy to use.  Now I don't care if Google fixes that glitch or not!

This app works perfectly. Creates a mini web server on your phone and the web interface is intuitive and easy to use. The connecting device - whether it be a computer of another phone - doesn't have to be connected to WiFi; it only needs to be able to access the device running WiFi File Transfer Pro. In fact I'm writing this review while uploading a bunch of files to my phone from my laptop that is connected via an Ethernet cable to my company network. I'm using a Motorola Droid RAZR HD as my phone.  In fact, this app made me realize that, along with WiFi Direct, an external SD card is not needed. That was a feature I absolutely needed when I was searching for a new smartphone a few months back. But I never owned a smartphone before I bought my RAZR and just figured I'd need an SD card to easily transfer files. Apps like this make it stupidly easy to move files back and forth. So, when looking for my next smartphone in a year or so from now, I'll ignore the SD card option.

The interface, the functionality is brilliant.    The problem:  None of the traffic is encrypted. So when you set an access password, when the user enters the password in the browser; it is transmitted in the clear.   Not a big deal on private trusted networks, but when you are using it on a foreign network, it is something to think about as anyone on the network who knows the ip address of the device can access and change your files if:   - You leave it accidently running in the background   - Some one manages to intercept your packets and reads your password    If this security issue was addressed, I'd give it 5 stars
